com.netflix.fenzo.queues.tiered

Class TieredQueue

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.netflix.fenzo.queues.tiered.TieredQueue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    InternalTaskQueue, TaskQueue, TaskIterator

    public class TieredQueue
extends java.lang.Object
implements InternalTaskQueue
    A tiered queuing system where queues are arranged in multiple tiers and then among multiple buckets within each tier. Tiers represent coarse grain priority, in which higher tier's queues are considered for resource assignment before any of the lower tiers' queues are considered. Within a tier, multiple queues are considered for resource assignment such that their dominant resource usage shares are similar. For example, a queue bucket using 60% of the total memory in use is said to be similar in usage to another bucket using 60% of the total CPUs in use, even if the latter's memory usage is, say, only 10%. The tiers are numbered 0 to N-1 for N tiers, with 0 being the highest priority level.

      • queueTask

        public void queueTask(QueuableTask task)
        Description copied from interface: TaskQueue
        Add a task to the queue. Duplicates are not allowed, as in, a task request that has the same Id as another existing element will be rejected. The added task will be assigned resources by a scheduler. To add a task into Fenzo that is already running from before, use TaskSchedulingService.initializeRunningTask(QueuableTask, String).

        This operation is designed to be performed asynchronously, when it is safe to modify the queue. The queue implementations generally do not modify the queue while a scheduling iteration is in progress.

        Specified by:
        queueTask in interface TaskQueue
        Parameters:
        task - A task to add to the queue.

      • remove

        public void remove(java.lang.String taskId,
                   QAttributes qAttributes)
        Description copied from interface: TaskQueue
        Remove a task from queue with the given taskId and qAttributes. The task is removed from the queue, whether it is marked as queued for assignments or already marked as running. This must be called for all tasks that either no longer need resource assignments or if previously running tasks complete for any reason.

        This operation is designed to be performed asynchronously, when it is safe to modify the queue. The queue implementations generally do not modify the queue while a scheduling iteration is in progress.

        Specified by:
        remove in interface TaskQueue
        Parameters:

      • next

        public QueuableTask next()
                  throws TaskQueueException
        This implementation dynamically picks the next task to consider for resource assignment based on tiers and then based on current dominant resource usage. The usage is updated with each resource assignment during the scheduling iteration, in addition to updating with all running jobs from before.
        Specified by:

        Reset the queue and make it ready for next scheduling iteration. Any operations requested that were not safe to carry out during a scheduling iteration can be carried out during this method, before the next scheduling iteration begins.
